
                                            South Africa has been named as the favourite to host the tournament and is competing against France and Ireland.
                                         JOHANNESBURG - Deputy president Cyril Ramaphosa says that the government is committed to ensuring that the 2023 Rugby World Cup is brought to South Africa. Ramaphosa will on Monday lead Team South Africa to London ahead of Wednesday’s much anticipated announcement by World Rugby about the World Cup host. South Africa has been named as the favourite and is competing against France and Ireland. Ramaphosa’s spokesperson Tyrone Seal says: “The deputy president’s participation and leadership in this visit will once again demonstrate government support for and commitment to return the tournament to the African continent in the 21 century.”